QUESTION:\
Logical Operations\
\
(a) Find out if the two expressions !(a) && !(b) and !(a && b) are equivalent?\
\
ANSWER \
To check whether !(a) && !(b) and !(a && b) are equivalent, we need to understand Boolean logic and apply De Morgan's Laws.\
\
1. Meaning of Expressions:\
\
!(a) && !(b) means both a is false and b is false.\
\
!(a && b) means it is not the case that both a and b are true, i.e., at least one of them is false.\
\
\
2. Applying De Morgan's Law:\
\
De Morgan's Law states:\
\
!(a && b) is equivalent to !a || !b\
\
!(a || b) is equivalent to !a && !b\
\
\
So:\
\
!(a && b) \uc0\u8801  !a || !b\
\
!(a) && !(b) \uc0\u8801  !(a || b)\
\
\
Therefore, !(a) && !(b) is not the same as !(a && b).\
\
\
Code to Demonstrate:\
\
public class LogicalOperationsTest \{\
    public static void main(String[] args) \{\
        boolean[] values = \{true, false\};\
\
        System.out.println("a\\tb\\t!(a)&&!(b)\\t!(a&&b)");\
        System.out.println("------------------------------------");\
\
        for (boolean a : values) \{\
            for (boolean b : values) \{\
                boolean expr1 = (!a) && (!b);\
                boolean expr2 = !(a && b);\
                System.out.println(a + "\\t" + b + "\\t" + expr1 + "\\t\\t" + expr2);\
            \}\
        \}\
    \}\
\}\
\
\
