true	    false	    false	     true\
false	true	    false	     true\
false	false    true		true\
\
As you can see, the two expressions produce different outputs in some cases. Hence, they are not logically equivalent.\
\
\
Final Conclusion:\
\
The expressions !(a) && !(b) and !(a && b) are not equivalent. This is a fundamental concept in logic that plays a critical role in conditions, programming, and mathematical reasoning.\
